President Reagan has identified welfare reform as a priority during
his final three years in office.

Several million families are involved in a cycle of poverty and
dependency.  Taxpayers have become impatient with the huge sums of
money (100 billion dollars per annum) that go to welfare with no
improvement in sight.

In response, the administration has agreed to give the states leeway
in devising their own plans.

There is a belief that the democrats in Congress are not serious about
reform.

With the support of the governors and the public, however, the
president could press the Congress to act.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ870227-0149"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

There is a definite need for welfare reform but the problem is what to
do about it.  The nation's governors are trying to get the
U.S. administration to accept their plan. They want a more
job-oriented scheme to require welfare recipients to work.

There was a surprising amount of agreement at a recent meeting between
the president and the governors. One area of presidential disagreement
was on a minimum level of benefits.

The price of the governors' plan is 2 billion dollars, which taxpayers
would view with skepticism. The ultimate goal of any plan is to escape
welfare dependency.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ871215-0109"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

The House of Representatives is scheduled to vote shortly on a new 5.2
billion dollar welfare spending bill.  It is described as a reform
bill but in reality, it pays only lip service to welfare reform.

The bill's proponents view the bill as a necessary expenditure for
special education, training and work programs for welfare mothers to
encourage them to find jobs.

Both parties in the House of Representatives believe that
welfare-to-work programs are valuable; however, the number of
long-term welfare dependents has increased.  Valid welfare reform
should shrink the number of welfare dependents and enhance the work
ethic.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880903-0092"
