SUMMARIZER="E"> 

President Reagan has informed the Congress that he will veto any
welfare reform legislation that does not contain a work requirement.

Although unemployment remains at one of its lowest levels in years,
the president believes that there are still people caught in the
welfare trap.  He is urging the states to design their own plans for
getting people off of welfare.

Democrats favor a current House-passed bill that would make welfare
recipients who work better off than those who do not.  This bill
leaves the requirement that a recipient work to state and local
governments which administer the programs.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT931-11394"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

President Clinton will form a task force shortly that will reform
welfare programs.  His reform includes expanded job training for the
unemployed and a requirement that people work for their welfare
checks.  Health coverage and other benefits would continue.

Welfare reformers fear that the Democratic emphasis on requiring
recipients to work or enroll in training might be canceled in favor of
more funding for current programs.  This would come at a time when
state revenues are limited due to recession and welfare rolls have
increased by 30 percent.

Many states have already begun their own welfare reform
programs.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT933-6011"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

The pledge to "end welfare as we know it" and the two-year limit on
welfare checks were pre-election themes voiced by President Clinton.

Americans view welfare as an evil of society and there is considerable
pressure to reduce it.

Two congressional actions may reduce welfare rolls and shift people
off welfare by making work pay.

Many conservatives favor a time limit for welfare. They feel this will
change behavior.

Strict measures for timely welfare reduction may be too
harsh. Conversely, a more gradual and humane phase-in would take
years.

Perhaps the goals set in the first instance were too high.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-11014"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

The federal government has given approval to Georgia and Wisconsin to
implement pilot programs for welfare reform.  These programs may serve
as experiments for the revamping of the federal welfare system.

The Wisconsin plan includes the discontinuance of payments under the
program Aid to Families of Dependent Children after two years.

The Georgia plan reduces welfare payments to all able-bodied adults
who refuse to work and denies any increases to families on long-term
welfare who have more children.

The Clinton administration is considering a two-year limit as a
standard for welfare benefits in fulfilling its promise for welfare
reform.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d12"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-12800"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="E"> 

Capitalist economies of the Organization of Economic Cooperation And
Development (OECD) are faced with ever-increasing costs of welfare.

Social security payments have doubled, as have healthcare costs. The
costliest item is pensions. Solutions include reduced benefits,
raising the retirement age, discontinuing cost of living increases and
control of drug costs.

Demographic changes such as increases in life expectancy, and
one-parent families lead to increased welfare costs.

Unemployment is a particularly difficult problem.

OECD states may not be able to afford current welfare systems in the
future but merely provide a means of caring for those unable to care
for themselves.</SUM>
